<section xml:id="section-complex-root-of-quadratic-functions">

    <title>Complex Roots of Quadratic Functions</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>When we solve a quadratic equation, sometimes there are no real solutions. In this case the solutions are imaginary or complex. In this section, we will look at the relationship between the graph of a function and complex solutions.</p>
        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <sbsgroup>
                <sidebyside>
                    <video youtube="zb-PYxwjGrg" />
                </sidebyside>
                <sidebyside>
                    <video youtube="11EwTcRMPn8" />
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Equations with Complex Solutions</title>

        <!-- TODO: Where do we first define solutions and roots? -->

        <p>Let's look at an application where we will determine whether the solutions are real or complex. In a stunt plane performance, a pilot plans to dive the plane toward the ground and then back up. The plane's height can be modeled by a quadratic function. If one possible function is <m>h(t)=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+12</m>, where <m>t</m> stands for time in seconds since the stunt begins, check whether the plane will hit the ground during the stunt.</p>

        <p>To check whether the plane will hit the ground during the stunt, we will solve the equation <m>h(t)=0</m>. We will solve this equation by completing the square. We will multiply both sides by <m>2</m> to remove the leading coefficient.</p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="middle">
        <p><md>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+12\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}\left(\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+12\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}0</mrow>
            <mrow>t^2-10t+24\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>t^2-10t\amp=-24</mrow>
            <mrow>t^2-10t\addright{(-5)^2}\amp=-24\addright{(-5)^2}</mrow>
            <mrow>(t-5)^2\amp=-24+25</mrow>
            <mrow>(t-5)^2\amp=1</mrow></md><md>
            <mrow>t-5\amp=-\sqrt{1}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp t-5\amp=\sqrt{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=5-1\amp\text{or}\amp\amp t\amp=5+1</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=4\amp\text{or}\amp\amp t\amp=6</mrow></md></p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Graph of <m>y=h(t)</m></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image >
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=3,xmin=-1,xmax=8,
                                ytick={-1,0,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-1,0,...,2},
                                xtick={1,2,...,7},
                                minor xtick={1,2,...,8},
                                xlabel={seconds},ylabel={feet}]
                        \addplot [<->, black, domain=2.354:7.646, samples=200] {0.5*x^2-5*x+12} node[pos=0.5,below,black] {$y=h(t)$};
                        \addplot [soliddot, color=black] coordinates {(4,0)};
                        \addplot [soliddot, color=black] coordinates {(6,0)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image >
            </image>

        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

        <p>This equation has two real solutions and we can see from the graph that the real solutions are the <m>t</m>-intercepts. the solution <m>t=4</m> shows that the plane would hit the ground <m>4</m> seconds into the stunt.</p>

        <p>To avoid hitting the ground, the pilot adjusted the function to <m>p(t)=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+12.5</m>. Let's see whether the plane would still hit the ground by solving the equation <m>0=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+12.5</m>. This time, we will use the quadratic formula to solve this equation. We identify that <m>a=0.5</m>, <m>b=-5</m> and <m>c=12.5</m>.</p>

    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="middle">
        <p><md>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-(-5)\pm\sqrt{(-5)^2-4(0.5)(12.5)}}{2(0.5)}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{5\pm\sqrt{25-25}}{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{5\pm\sqrt{0}}{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{5}{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=5</mrow></md></p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Graph of <m>y=p(t)</m></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image >
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=3,xmin=-1,xmax=8,
                                ytick={-1,0,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-1,0,...,2},
                                xtick={1,2,...,7},
                                minor xtick={1,2,...,8},
                                xlabel={seconds},ylabel={feet}]
                        \addplot [<->, blue, domain=2.551:7.449, samples=200] {0.5*x^2-5*x+12.5} node[pos=0.5,above,blue] {$y=p(t)$};
                        \addplot [soliddot, color=blue] coordinates {(5,0)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image >
            </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

        <p>This equation has one real solution and one <m>x</m>-intercept. This time the plane would hit the ground <m>5</m> seconds into the stunt.</p>

        <p>Let's adjust the function to <m>q(t)=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+13</m> and solve the equation <m>0=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+13</m>. Since the quadratic formula is easier, we will use it again. Identify that <m>a=0.5</m>, <m>b=-5</m> and <m>c=13</m>.</p>

    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="middle">
        <p><md>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-(-5)\pm\sqrt{(-5)^2-4(0.5)(13)}}{2(0.5)}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=\frac{5\pm\sqrt{25-26}}{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=5\pm\sqrt{-1}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=5\pm i</mrow></md></p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Graph of <m>y=q(t)</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <description></description>
                <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=3,xmin=-1,xmax=8,
                                ytick={-1,0,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-1,0,...,2},
                                xtick={1,2,...,7},
                                minor xtick={1,2,...,8},
                                xlabel={seconds},ylabel={feet}]
                        \addplot [<->, red, domain=2.764:7.236, samples=200] {0.5*x^2-5*x+13} node[pos=0.5,above,red] {$q(t)$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

        <p>In this context, when we see the negative radicand we can stop and conclude that the equation has no real solutions. This means there are no x-intercepts and the plane will not touch the ground. If we want to go further we need to go into the complex number system and then there are two complex solutions.</p>

        <p>Here is a summary of what we found:<ul>
            <li><p>When a quadratic function <m>h(t)</m> has two <m>x</m>-intercepts, the equation <m>h(t)=0</m> has two real solutions.</p></li>
            <li><p>When a quadratic function <m>p(t)</m> has one <m>x</m>-intercept, the equation <m>p(t)=0</m> has one real solution.</p></li>
            <li><p>When a quadratic function <m>q(t)</m> has no <m>x</m>-intercepts, the equation <m>q(t)=0</m> has no real solutions, but it has two complex solutions.</p></li>
        </ul></p>

        <p>Here are some more examples of solving equations with complex solutions.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>s</m> in <m>s^2-10s=-34</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The value of <m>b</m> is even so we will complete the square and add <m>5^2</m> to both sides<md>
                    <mrow>s^2-10s\amp=-34</mrow>
                    <mrow>s^2-10s\addright{5^2}\amp=-34\addright{5^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>(s-5)^2\amp=-34+25</mrow>
                    <mrow>(s-5)^2\amp=-9</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>s-5\amp=-\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{-1}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp s-5\amp=\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{-1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>s-5\amp=-3i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp s-5\amp=3i</mrow>
                    <mrow>s\amp=5-3i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp s\amp=5+3i</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
        <p>The Quadratic Formula can also be used to solve for complex solutions. Here is an example where it makes more sense to use the quadratic formula.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>5x^2-3x=-7</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To complete the square we would divide both sides by <m>5</m>, but that would give us fractions. Instead, we will put the equation in standard form to use the quadratic formula.<md>
                    <mrow>5x^2-3x\amp=-7</mrow>
                    <mrow>5x^2-3x+7\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>We identify that <m>a=5</m>, <m>b=-3</m> and <m>c=7</m> and substitute them into the Quadratic Formula:<md>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-(-3)\pm\sqrt{(-3)^2-4(5)(7)}}{2(5)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{3\pm\sqrt{9-140}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{3\pm\sqrt{-131}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{3\pm\sqrt{-1\cdot131}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{3\pm\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{131}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{3\pm i\sqrt{131}}{10}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

<!-- TODO: This one can be interactive -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>2x^2+12x+26=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will complete the square because after dividing both sides by <m>2</m>, the value of <m>b</m> will be even. Then we will add <m>3^2</m> to both sides of the equation:<md>
                    <mrow>2x^2+12x\amp=-26</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2+6x\amp=-13</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2+6s\addright{3^2}\amp=-13\addright{3^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x+3)^2\amp=-13+9</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x+3)^2\amp=-4</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>x+3\amp=-\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{-1}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+3\amp=\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{-1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x+3\amp=-2i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+3\amp=2i</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=-3-2i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-3+2i</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

